ssey of Louie Fats -- tATTICKA ATTICKA -- tSynopsis of a Hummingbird -- tRise On -- tMercy Killing -- tCity Interlude -- t/PRISON POETS/ -- tA Stretch-Sketch -- tWeekend in a Springhill Mine -- tThe Battle of Joe Meek -- tSounds of Silence -- t“ The Death of Bang-Bang Charlie” -- tShadows -- tPalm Sunday -- t“Olé” -- tApplause to Archie Shepp & Co. -- tThe End of Summer -- tTwelve Past the Hour of Forty-Three: Attica — Sept. 13, 1971 -- tEpilogue: Remember This -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix: Workshop Documents0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFollowing the Attica prison uprising in September 1971, Celes Tisdale—a poet and then professor at Buffalo State College—began leading poetry workshops with those incarcerated at Attica. Tisdale’s workshop created a space of radical Black creativity and solidarity, in which poets who lived through the uprising were able to turn their experiences into poetry. The poems written by Tisdale’s students were published as Betcha Ain’t: Poems from Attica in 1974. When the Smoke Cleared contains the entirety of Betcha Ain’t, Tisdale’s own poems and journal entries from the three years he taught at Attica, a previously unpublished collection of poems by Attica poets, and a critical introduction by poet Mark Nowak. In addition to the poetry, Tisdale’s journal entries give readers a unique opportunity to experience what it was like to enter Attica as an educator and return week after week to discuss poetry. When the Smoke Cleared showcases these poets’ achievements, their desire for self-determination, and their historical role as storytellers of Black life in a prison monitored exclusively by white guards and administrators.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAmerican poetryzNew York (State)zAttic